element.name: Rath Maeve by Windsockers, Traditional Cache (2/2)

center.b: Queen Maeve on an Irish Punt

long-description.p:
This Hill fort is named after Queen Maeve,it originally measured approximately 250 metres in diameter.
unfortunatley this site which is obviously connected to Tara has been very neglected all that remains now is a well preserved embankment near the road leading to Tara.
Queen Maeve was queen of Connacht during the Iron Age.

Queen Maeve has many names among the druids of Ireland some of which include Mab/Mabh/Meda(meev)/Medh/Medhbh. She is considered the "Drunken Woman" or the "Queen-wolf". But nonetheless Maeve is the queen of the fairy whose name means "mead". Mead was a red drink or claret that she gave to her many consorts.
Queen Maeve was also a warrior queen of the Ulster cycle. She was a Goddess of War that actually participated in the fighting;combined with mother and warrior aspects of the goddess.
Maeve represents physical sexuality and fertility, revenge, and war!
The Cache is a small contaner Please rehide the cache with care to prevent muggles from discovering its location.
